{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17637424","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17637424"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:42:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:42:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17658"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17658","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17658"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.42,0,0.35,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10372"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75878"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10372","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10372"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17658"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61391"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10526"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24257"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24298"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75878","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75878"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe micturition reflex involves coordination between the bladder, spinal cord, and brain stem to enable controlled urination.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the normal micturition reflex pathway?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bladder stretch signals travel directly to the cerebral cortex","Bladder stretch signals travel via pelvic nerves to sacral spinal cord then pons","Bladder stretch signals travel via sympathetic nerves to thoracic spinal cord","Bladder stretch signals travel via pudendal nerves to lumbar spinal cord","Bladder stretch signals travel via hypogastric nerves to hypothalamus"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct pathway involves \u003Cstrong\u003Ebladder stretch signals travelling via pelvic nerves to sacral spinal cord then pons\u003C/strong\u003E. When the bladder fills, stretch receptors in the bladder wall activate, sending signals via pelvic nerves to neurons in the sacral spinal cord (S2-S4). These neurons then relay information to the pontine micturition centre, which coordinates the micturition reflex.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBladder stretch signals travel directly to the cerebral cortex\u003C/strong\u003E - Sensory signals from the bladder must first synapse in the spinal cord and brainstem before reaching the cortex.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBladder stretch signals travel via sympathetic nerves to thoracic spinal cord\u003C/strong\u003E - The sympathetic nervous system plays a minor role in bladder filling but is not the primary pathway for detecting bladder fullness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBladder stretch signals travel via pudendal nerves to lumbar spinal cord\u003C/strong\u003E - The pudendal nerve primarily provides motor control to the external urethral sphincter and does not carry bladder stretch signals.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBladder stretch signals travel via hypogastric nerves to hypothalamus\u003C/strong\u003E - The hypogastric nerves carry sympathetic signals and do not directly connect to the hypothalamus; bladder fullness is detected via the parasympathetic pathway.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe pontine micturition centre then coordinates bladder contraction with external urethral sphincter relaxation to allow urination. Higher centres in the cerebral cortex can voluntarily inhibit or facilitate this reflex.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The micturition reflex is initiated when bladder stretch receptors signal fullness via pelvic nerves to the sacral spinal cord.","The pontine micturition centre coordinates bladder contraction with external urethral sphincter relaxation.","Voluntary control of micturition involves higher centres inhibiting or facilitating the pontine micturition centre."],"references":["Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020.","Tortora, G. J., Mellifont, R., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Peoples, G., D, D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition,  2nd Edition. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61391"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17658"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61391","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61391"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-01T07:50:48+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-01T07:50:48+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10372"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75878"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position